<br>
I recall my discussions back in college with a colleague who believed that it was possible to move completely away from capitalism to a society where anything one needed was available at no cost.  My response was:  &quot;how will these things be prioritized if, looking at things realisticly, there are not infinite supplies of all things?&quot;<br>
<br>
That was the sticking point, and is the reason why communistic societies tend to fail.  It is human nature to want to better one's place in society and one's security overall.  We tend to do this by providing for any future dearth of supply by creating a surplus from which we may draw.  A good example of this is in most individuals' refrigerators.<br>
<br>
However, in a true commune everyone has exactly what they need and there is no surplus other than the communal surplus.  All individuals are equal and have an equal say in how the community is run.<br>
<br>
Athens was a good example of why this form of decision making didn't work so well, even if it wasn't a commune.  Athens, as a democracy, required a vote before anything occurred.  However, it became necessary in times of war for a tyrant to take power for the duration of the war and then for that tyrant to be deposed following the war if he would not step down voluntarily.  So, in practice, not even Athens could maintain a pure democracy and it was just a city.<br>
<br>
On the largest scale NO pure governmental method works.  Fascism falls apart because it largely depends on the popular support of the population.  Once you get over a few millions, any disgruntled percentage is large enough to launch a rebellion.  Dictatorships fall apart because there's no good way to transfer loyalty to a single leader.  Monarchies tend to fall apart because they foster elitism and disenfranchisement.  Oligarchies fail because they inevitably turn into dictatorships (which are then overthrown).  <br>
<br>
Of all the developed forms of government, the Nationalist Republic seems to be the most enduring.  However, it is my suspicion that even republics cannot stand the test of time, for no other reason than because it is human nature to attempt to gain control of our environment, and that includes political systems.  Every free society is simply an attempt to stave off dictatorship, tyrrany, and oppression.  I sadly believe that regardless of the nature of the government, these forces eventually hold sway, are overthrown, and are replaced.<br>
<br>
I invite differing views. <p>Fritz Darkweaver<BR>
Wood Elven Scout of Tunare<BR>
